Schottland’s private schools’ learning results have traditionally been good, and this success has continued in 2018 as a result of good test results. The success has been reinforced by individual and community success in sport, art, music and other community projects.
Over 30,000 schools, represented by the Board of Private Schools of Scotland (SCIS), are located across Scotland to provide a high level of service to their pupils and to the parents of their pupils.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for their chosen careers, higher education and higher education, as well as global citizenship.
As an actor in the education sector, who can design and implement customized learning content, we have noticed the status of languages as a preferred and desired subject of continuous learning in educational institutions.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a person in a language that he understands, the message goes to his head.
If you speak to a person in his own language, the message goes to his heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely only on English if we want to build relationships of trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s latest test results, we find that languages are at the top of the lists in terms of the percentage of access among private schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved the highest score of A.
The material was collected from 74 SCIS schools. Based on the material, 72 per cent of the students who received the best grade A studied Mandarin, 72 per cent studied German, 69 per cent studied French and 63 per cent studied Spanish.
This shows that private schools in Scotland support foreign language learning as an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are currently subjects of choice, but they are held at the same value as natural sciences (science, technology, engineering and mathematics), both in the private school curriculum and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment Agency found that 17 per cent of situations where the employer had difficulty finding a suitable employee for the job were explained by a lack of language skills.
The development of language skills is therefore even more necessary for the advancement of the future career of young people.
The more potential jobs require linguistic skills, the more essential these skills are formed in the global world.
If a person has studied a second language, he/she will have a priority in the future on this lifelong skill, no matter what career he/she has chosen.
The ability to communicate directly with a foreigner to automatically put a linguistic person ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent of them are unable to talk in a foreign language, and French was the only language that could speak a two-digit figure of 15 percent.
This is why investing in language learning is important for today’s children.
In particular, knowledge of the languages of developing countries gives children a better opportunity to find a meaningful career.
Within Scotland, schools differ in what languages they teach each other.
Several schools focus on traditional languages, while some specifically teach languages that are expected to be important to the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Despite the interests of your child, there are always a number of language options in the private schools taught by specialized teachers.
Scottish private schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future brings when it comes.
At this time, it cannot be denied that languages in the international business environment are still very important for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Today’s languages should indeed be seen as ‘international communication skills’.
Private schools will continue to offer this freedom of choice, diversity and a high level of youth in Scotland.
