New Cancer Vaccine Able to Teach Immune System to ‘See’ Malignant Cells and Destroy them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to identify malignant cells as part of treatment
In the method, resistant cells are isolated from the patient and altered in the laboratory
After treatment, cells injected back into the body are able to “see” the typical proteins for many cancers
Dog vaccination has yielded promising results in different cancer patients.
For example, the cancer cells of a patient with ovarian cancer disappeared within 18 months of being treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to identify malignant cells.
In this method, the resistant cells are isolated from the patient and modified in the laboratory so that they are able to ‘see’ the typical HER2 proteins that are common to many cancers. The transformed cells are finally injected back into the body.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, United States, describes the method: "Based on our results, this is a very promising vaccine."
HER2 "controls the growth of several cancers," explains Professor Berzofsky. "These include breast cancer as well as eating of the ovaries, lungs and colon."
A similar approach – taking resistant cells from the patient and teaching them to attack cancer cells – has also produced results in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
